Preheat the #oven to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7. Boil a large #pot of salted @water{to taste}.

Trim the @aubergine{1} and cut into 2cm pieces.

Pop the aubergine onto a lined #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{to taste}, season with @paprika{2%sachets}, @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste} then toss to coat. Spread out in a single layer.

When oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until the aubergine is soft and golden, ~{20-25%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

> TIP: To save time you can boil the water in your kettle.

Meanwhile, chop the @sweet potato{2} into 2cm chunks (peeling optional).

When boiling, add the sweet potatoes to the water and cook until fork tender, ~{15-20%minutes}.

Place a large #pan over medium-high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}. Season the @pork loin steak{300%grams} with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and equipment after handling raw meat. Pork is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Once hot, fry the pork until browned, ~{2-3%minutes} on each side.

Lower heat to medium and cook for an additional ~{4-6%minutes}, turning every couple of mins.

Once cooked, remove from pan, cover with #foil and allow to rest.

When everything is almost ready, return the pan to medium-high heat with @butter{2%tbsp}. Pick the @sage{10%grams} leaves from their stalks (keeping them whole). Discard the stalks.

When the butter is melted, add the sage leaves to the pan and fry until crispy, ~{2-3%minutes}, shifting as they cook.

Once crisp, add the pork back to the pan. Carefully use a #spoon to baste the pork in the sage butter.

Once the potatoes are cooked, drain in a #colander and return to the pot, off the heat.

Add a knob of @butter{to taste} and a splash of @?milk{to taste} or @water{to taste}.

Mash with a #potato masher{} until smooth. Season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

Plate up your succulent pork steaks.

Serve sweet potato mash and roasted aubergine alongside.

Drizzle any remaining sage butter over the pork.